{
  "What is crystallization?": "",
  "A process where a dissolved substance forms solid crystals from a solution": "",
  "A process where a solid is broken down into a liquid by applying strong heat": "",
  "A process where two liquids are separated based on their different densities": "",
  "A process where a gas is converted directly into a solid by strong compression": "",
  "Crystallization is the process where dissolved solute particles come together and form an organized solid structure (crystals) as the solution cools or the solvent evaporates.": "",
  "What is filtration?": "",
  "A method of heating a liquid until it completely evaporates": "",
  "A method of separating a solid from a liquid using a filter": "",
  "A method of cooling a gas until it becomes a liquid substance": "",
  "A method of dissolving a solid in water to make a clear solution": "",
  "Filtration is a separation technique that uses a porous barrier (like filter paper) to trap solid particles while allowing the liquid to pass through.": "",
  "What must happen to a solution before crystals can form?": "",
  "It must become unsaturated by adding more solvent to the mix": "",
  "It must become saturated or supersaturated with dissolved solute": "",
  "It must be heated to its boiling point and kept there for an hour": "",
  "It must be placed under high pressure in a sealed metal container": "",
  "For crystals to form, the solution must become saturated (holding the maximum dissolved solute) or supersaturated (holding more than normal). Cooling or evaporation causes excess solute to crystallize out.": "",
  "What is the solid material left on the filter paper after filtration called?": "",
  "The filtrate": "",
  "The distillate": "",
  "The residue": "",
  "The solvent": "",
  "The solid trapped by the filter paper is called the residue. The liquid that passes through is called the filtrate.": "",
  "How does cooling a hot saturated solution cause crystals to form?": "",
  "Cold water can hold more dissolved substance, so crystals dissolve": "",
  "Cold water holds less dissolved substance, so excess comes out as crystals": "",
  "The cold temperature freezes the water and traps the solute in ice crystals": "",
  "Cooling causes a chemical reaction that converts the solute into solid crystals": "",
  "Most substances are less soluble in cold water than hot water. When a hot saturated solution cools, it can no longer hold as much dissolved solute, so the excess forms solid crystals.": "",
  "What common item is used as a filter in a basic filtration setup?": "",
  "Aluminum foil": "",
  "Plastic wrap": "",
  "Filter paper": "",
  "Wax paper": "",
  "Filter paper is a porous paper specially designed to allow liquids to pass through while trapping solid particles. It is placed in a funnel during the filtration process.": "",
  "Which type of mixture can filtration separate?": "",
  "A mixture of two miscible liquids blended together": "",
  "A mixture of an insoluble solid and a liquid together": "",
  "A mixture of two different gases mixed in a container": "",
  "A mixture of dissolved salt and water in a beaker now": "",
  "Filtration works best for separating an insoluble solid from a liquid. The solid particles are too large to pass through the filter paper, while the liquid flows through.": "",
  "Making rock candy by growing sugar crystals on a string is an example of which process?": "",
  "Filtration": "",
  "Distillation": "",
  "Crystallization": "",
  "Chromatography": "",
  "Rock candy is made by dissolving sugar in hot water to create a supersaturated solution. As the solution slowly cools and water evaporates, sugar crystals grow on the string.": "",
  "Why does a funnel hold the filter paper during filtration?": "",
  "The funnel adds chemicals that help separate the solid from the liquid": "",
  "The funnel supports the paper and directs the filtrate into a container": "",
  "The funnel heats the mixture so the liquid evaporates more efficiently": "",
  "The funnel makes the solid particles smaller so they pass through the paper": "",
  "The funnel provides physical support for the filter paper and channels the liquid filtrate downward into the collection container below.": "",
  "Which factor most affects the size of crystals that form during crystallization?": "",
  "The color of the solute being crystallized from the solution": "",
  "The speed at which the solution cools down during the process": "",
  "The type of container used to hold the solution while cooling": "",
  "The room lighting present during the crystallization experiment": "",
  "Slow cooling allows more time for solute particles to arrange in an orderly pattern, producing larger crystals. Rapid cooling creates many small crystals because particles have less time to organize.": "",
  "What is a saturated solution?": "",
  "A solution that contains the maximum amount of dissolved solute at a given temperature": "",
  "A solution that has no solute dissolved in it and is made only of pure solvent liquid": "",
  "A solution that has been heated to its boiling point and is actively producing vapor": "",
  "A solution that contains two or more different solvents mixed together in one container": "",
  "A saturated solution holds the maximum amount of dissolved solute at a specific temperature. Adding more solute will cause it to remain undissolved at the bottom.": "",
  "What is a supersaturated solution?": "",
  "A solution containing more dissolved solute than it normally can hold at that temperature": "",
  "A solution that has been diluted with extra water until it is very weak in concentration": "",
  "A solution that has been frozen solid and no longer contains any liquid solvent at all": "",
  "A solution that contains exactly half the maximum amount of solute it could possibly hold": "",
  "A supersaturated solution contains more dissolved solute than is normally possible at that temperature. It is unstable and can crystallize suddenly when disturbed or when a seed crystal is added.": "",
  "What does 'solute' mean?": "",
  "The substance that is dissolved in a solution": "",
  "The liquid that does the dissolving in a solution": "",
  "The solid left behind after filtration is complete": "",
  "The gas produced when a solution is heated up high": "",
  "The solute is the substance that dissolves in a solvent to form a solution. For example, in saltwater, salt is the solute and water is the solvent.": "",
  "What does 'insoluble' mean?": "",
  "Able to dissolve easily in a particular solvent to form a clear solution": "",
  "Unable to dissolve in a particular solvent and remaining as a separate solid": "",
  "Able to melt when heated to a temperature above its normal melting point": "",
  "Unable to be filtered because the particles are too small for filter paper": "",
  "An insoluble substance does not dissolve in a given solvent. Sand is insoluble in water, which is why filtration can separate sand from water.": "",
  "What is a 'seed crystal'?": "",
  "A small crystal added to a solution to encourage more crystals to grow around it": "",
  "The first liquid drop that passes through filter paper during a filtration process": "",
  "A type of mineral found in soil that plants use as nutrients for their growth": "",
  "A chemical substance added to a solution to help dissolve more solute in the mix": "",
  "A seed crystal is a small crystal introduced into a supersaturated solution to trigger crystallization. Dissolved solute particles arrange themselves around the seed, growing larger crystals.": "",
  "What does 'solubility' mean?": "",
  "The maximum amount of solute that can dissolve in a given amount of solvent at a specific temperature": "",
  "The speed at which a solid substance dissolves when placed into a liquid solvent at room temperature": "",
  "The ability of a filter to trap solid particles and prevent them from passing through the paper": "",
  "The temperature at which a substance changes from a solid state into a liquid state of matter": "",
  "Solubility is the maximum amount of solute that can dissolve in a specific amount of solvent at a given temperature. It usually increases with temperature for solid solutes.": "",
  "What does 'filtrate' mean?": "",
  "The solid material that remains trapped on the filter paper surface": "",
  "The liquid that passes through the filter during the filtration process": "",
  "The funnel that holds the filter paper during the filtration experiment": "",
  "The crystals that form when a saturated solution is cooled down slowly": "",
  "The filtrate is the liquid that successfully passes through the filter paper during filtration. It should be free of the insoluble solid particles that were trapped.": "",
  "What does 'residue' mean in filtration?": "",
  "The clear liquid collected beneath the filter funnel in the flask": "",
  "The filter paper itself that is used in the separation procedure": "",
  "The solid material left behind on the filter after the liquid passes": "",
  "The solvent used to dissolve the solute before performing filtration": "",
  "The residue is the solid that remains on the filter paper after filtration. It consists of the insoluble particles that were too large to pass through the pores.": "",
  "What does 'crystal lattice' mean?": "",
  "The repeating, orderly three-dimensional arrangement of particles in a crystal": "",
  "The random, disordered arrangement of particles found in a liquid substance": "",
  "The type of filter paper used in laboratory filtration experiments conducted": "",
  "The container used to collect the filtrate after it passes through the filter": "",
  "A crystal lattice is the highly organized, repeating three-dimensional pattern of atoms, ions, or molecules in a crystal. This ordered structure gives crystals their regular geometric shapes.": "",
  "What does 'recrystallization' mean?": "",
  "Dissolving impure crystals in hot solvent and then crystallizing again to get purer crystals": "",
  "Breaking crystals apart into smaller pieces using a mortar and pestle in the chemistry lab": "",
  "Melting crystals completely so they turn into a liquid and lose their crystal shape forever": "",
  "Mixing different types of crystals together to form a new compound with new properties": "",
  "Recrystallization is a purification technique where impure crystals are dissolved in hot solvent, filtered to remove insoluble impurities, then cooled to form purer crystals.": "",
  "A student wants to recover pure salt from a mixture of salt and sand. Which combination of techniques should they use?": "",
  "Dissolve in water, filter to remove sand, then evaporate water to crystallize salt": "",
  "Heat the mixture until both salt and sand melt, then pour them into separate jars": "",
  "Use a magnet to attract the salt particles and leave the sand behind on the table": "",
  "Use chromatography paper to separate the salt from the sand by capillary action": "",
  "Add water to dissolve the salt (sand is insoluble), filter to remove the sand, then heat the saltwater to evaporate the water and crystallize the pure salt.": "",
  "A student dissolves a large amount of sugar in hot water and then lets the solution cool slowly with a string hanging inside. After several days, large sugar crystals coat the string. What process formed the crystals?": "",
  "Filtration, because the string acted like a filter trapping sugar from the water": "",
  "Distillation, because the water evaporated leaving the sugar on the string behind": "",
  "Crystallization, because cooling reduced solubility and sugar formed solid crystals": "",
  "Decomposition, because the sugar broke down into simpler substances on the string": "",
  "This is crystallization. The hot saturated sugar solution became supersaturated as it cooled, and excess sugar came out of solution as solid crystals that grew on the string.": "",
  "A chemist wants to purify a sample of copper sulfate crystals that contain some sand impurities. What sequence of steps should they follow?": "",
  "Dissolve in hot water, filter out the sand, then cool the solution to crystallize pure copper sulfate": "",
  "Heat the mixture until it melts, pour off the liquid copper sulfate, and let it cool into crystals": "",
  "Use a magnet to separate the copper sulfate from the sand, then wash with cold water to clean": "",
  "Use chromatography to separate copper sulfate and sand, then collect the copper sulfate spots": "",
  "This is recrystallization: dissolve the impure crystals in hot water, filter out the insoluble sand, then cool the filtrate to produce pure copper sulfate crystals.": "",
  "In a pharmaceutical lab, a scientist needs to separate a medicine crystal from a liquid mixture. The crystals are too fine to settle on their own. What technique should they use first?": "",
  "Distillation to evaporate the liquid and leave the crystals behind in the flask": "",
  "Vacuum filtration to quickly pull the liquid through a filter and collect the crystals": "",
  "Chromatography to separate the dissolved medicine from the liquid on paper strips": "",
  "Decanting to pour off the liquid carefully while the crystals float on the surface": "",
  "Vacuum filtration uses reduced pressure to pull the liquid through filter paper faster and more efficiently, making it ideal for collecting fine crystals that are suspended in liquid.": "",
  "A student rapidly cools a hot sugar solution by placing it in an ice bath. They get many tiny crystals instead of a few large ones. Why?": "",
  "Rapid cooling produces many small crystals because particles have less time to organize": "",
  "The ice bath chemically reacted with the sugar and broke it into smaller pieces overall": "",
  "The container was too small so the crystals could not grow to a full large size in it": "",
  "The student used too much water in the solution, which prevented large crystal growth": "",
  "Rapid cooling causes many crystal nuclei to form simultaneously, but each has little time to grow. Slow cooling allows fewer nuclei to form, and each grows into a larger, more organized crystal.": "",
  "A water treatment plant uses large sand filters to clean water. Why is sand an effective filter material?": "",
  "Sand chemically reacts with and destroys bacteria and viruses in the water supply": "",
  "Sand grains have small spaces between them that trap particles as water flows through": "",
  "Sand absorbs all chemicals dissolved in water and converts them to harmless substances": "",
  "Sand is magnetic and attracts impurities out of the water as it passes over the grains": "",
  "The small spaces between sand grains act as tiny filters, trapping suspended solid particles, debris, and some microorganisms as water passes through the bed.": "",
  "A geologist finds a cave with large quartz crystals. These crystals formed naturally over thousands of years. What conditions most likely helped them grow so large?": "",
  "Very rapid cooling of mineral-rich water trapped in the cave underground": "",
  "Very slow cooling over a long time with a steady supply of dissolved minerals": "",
  "Extremely high pressure that compressed tiny crystals into larger single ones": "",
  "Volcanic lava flowing through the cave and melting the rock into crystal shapes": "",
  "Large natural crystals form when mineral-rich solutions cool extremely slowly over long periods. This gives particles time to arrange into highly organized, large crystal structures.": "",
  "A student tries to filter a saltwater solution to separate the salt from the water. The filtrate is still salty. Why did filtration not work?": "",
  "The filter paper had holes that were too large and let the salt through easily": "",
  "Salt is dissolved in water, so its particles are too small for the filter to trap": "",
  "The student did not pour the solution slowly enough through the filter paper": "",
  "Saltwater cannot be separated by any method because it is a chemical compound": "",
  "Dissolved salt particles are at the molecular level — far too small for filter paper to trap. Filtration only works for insoluble solids. To recover salt, evaporation or crystallization is needed.": "",
  "A student drops a small crystal of potassium permanganate into a supersaturated solution. Suddenly, purple crystals form rapidly throughout the solution. What role did the small crystal play?": "",
  "It chemically reacted with the solution and created new purple crystal compounds": "",
  "It acted as a seed crystal that triggered crystallization of the excess dissolved solute": "",
  "It dyed the solution purple and the color change caused the solute to solidify quickly": "",
  "It lowered the temperature of the solution dramatically which forced all the crystals out": "",
  "The small crystal acted as a seed crystal. In a supersaturated solution, introducing a seed crystal provides a surface for excess dissolved solute to begin crystallizing rapidly.": "",
  "A coffee maker uses a paper filter to brew coffee. The dark liquid passes through while the grounds stay in the filter. A student says this is the same principle as lab filtration. Are they correct?": "",
  "No, coffee brewing is a chemical reaction and lab filtration is only physical separation": "",
  "No, coffee filters work by evaporation while lab filters work by trapping solid particles": "",
  "Yes, both use a porous barrier to separate insoluble solid particles from a liquid": "",
  "Yes, but only because coffee is technically considered a chemical compound not a mixture": "",
  "The student is correct. Coffee brewing uses filtration — hot water extracts soluble compounds from the grounds, and the paper filter traps the insoluble grounds while letting the brewed coffee through.": ""
